            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Simpson's Rule Formula</h2>
              <p>
                Simpson's rule is a numerical integration method that
                approximates the definite integral \(\displaystyle \int_a^b
                f(x)\,dx\) by fitting parabolas through the function values.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  For an even number of subintervals \(n\) and step size \(h =
                  \dfrac{b-a}{n}\):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \approx S_n = \frac{h}{3}\left[ f(x_0) +
                  f(x_n) + 4\sum_{i=1,\,\text{odd}}^{n-1} f(x_i) +
                  2\sum_{i=2,\,\text{even}}^{n-2} f(x_i) \right] \]
                </p>
                <p>where \(x_i = a + i h\).</p>
              </div>

              <h3>When to use Simpson's rule</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>The integrand is reasonably smooth on \([a,b]\).</li>
                <li>You cannot easily find an antiderivative symbolically.</li>
                <li>
                  You want higher accuracy than the trapezoidal or midpoint rule
                  for the same number of points.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Error behavior</h3>
              <p>
                If \(f\) has a continuous fourth derivative on \([a,b]\), the
                error of Simpson's rule satisfies
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ E_S = \int_a^b f(x)\,dx - S_n \approx -\frac{(b-a)}{180} h^4
                f^{(4)}(\xi) \quad \text{for some } \xi \in (a,b), \]
              </div>
              <p>
                so the error is on the order of \(h^4\). Halving the step size
                (doubling \(n\)) typically reduces the error by a factor of
                about \(2^4 = 16\) for smooth functions.
              </p>

              <h2>How to use this Simpson's Rule Calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the function.</strong> Type your integrand into
                  the <strong>f(x)</strong> field using standard math syntax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Set the limits.</strong> Enter the lower limit
                  <strong>a</strong> and upper limit <strong>b</strong> of
                  integration.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose n.</strong> Enter an even integer for the
                  number of subintervals. Start with 10–20, then increase if you
                  need more accuracy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Optional: enable refinement.</strong> Check “Refine
                  with 2n” to get a second approximation and an automatic error
                  estimate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click Calculate.</strong> View the numerical result,
                  the full Simpson sum table, and the graph of the function with
                  Simpson parabolas.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Approximate \(\displaystyle \int_0^\pi \sin(x)\,dx\) using
                Simpson's rule with \(n = 10\).
              </p>
              <p>
                Here \(a = 0\), \(b = \pi\), \(h = \dfrac{\pi - 0}{10} =
                \dfrac{\pi}{10}\).
              </p>
              <p>
                The nodes are \(x_i = i\pi/10\), \(i = 0,\dots,10\). Simpson's
                rule gives
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ S_{10} = \frac{h}{3}\left[ f(x_0) + f(x_{10}) +
                4(f(x_1)+f(x_3)+\dots+f(x_9)) + 2(f(x_2)+f(x_4)+\dots+f(x_8))
                \right]. \]
              </div>
              <p>
                The exact value of the integral is \(2\). With \(n=10\),
                Simpson's rule already gives an approximation extremely close to
                2, and increasing \(n\) quickly drives the error toward machine
                precision.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Why does n have to be even?</h3>
              <p>
                Simpson's rule uses quadratic polynomials that span two
                subintervals at a time and require three points \((x_{2k},
                x_{2k+1}, x_{2k+2})\). To tile the whole interval \([a,b]\) with
                such pairs, the total number of subintervals \(n\) must be even.
              </p>

              <h3>How large should n be?</h3>
              <p>
                There is no universal answer, but for many smooth functions,
                \(n\) between 20 and 200 is enough for high accuracy. Use the
                “Refine with 2n” option: if the two approximations are close,
                your result is likely accurate to that number of decimal places.
              </p>

              <h3>What functions are problematic for Simpson's rule?</h3>
              <p>Simpson's rule can struggle when:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  the function has discontinuities or sharp corners inside
                  \([a,b]\);
                </li>
                <li>the function has singularities (blows up to infinity);</li>
                <li>
                  the function oscillates extremely rapidly compared to your
                  step size.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In such cases, you may need to split the interval, increase
                \(n\) significantly, or use more specialized numerical
                integration methods.
              </p>
            </section>
